  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-not-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Not accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw, ASTM F1717 compression-bending) results in a Not-accepted decision based on documented shortfalls in two factors at modelRiskLevel 3. (1) Model form (required Gradation 3, achieved Gradation 2): The bilinear isotropic hardening constitutive model does not adequately represent the anisotropic post-yield behavior of machined non-cannulated Ti-6Al-4V screws, and the contact friction sensitivity was not characterized. This deficiency is directly evidenced by the yield force E/uval of 2.34, which exceeds the 1.96 acceptance threshold. (2) Model inputs (required Gradation 3, achieved Gradation 2): As-built specimen dimensions were not measured or statistically characterized for the N=11 test constructs; nominal CAD dimensions were used throughout, introducing unquantified geometric input error that contributes to the yield force prediction shortfall. These two shortfalls are structurally linked: the model form cannot be adequately assessed without specimen-specific input fidelity, and the combined effect produces a quantitatively demonstrated failure of the yield force acceptance criterion. The remaining 11 factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels, and the stiffness and force-at-40-mm QoIs pass their acceptance criteria. However, yield force is a primary regulatory QoI for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions, and the demonstrated prediction error at this QoI cannot be accepted without remediation. Recommended corrective actions prior to resubmission: (a) characterize as-built screw thread geometry for all test specimens via CMM measurement and incorporate specimen-specific inputs; (b) augment the constitutive model with anisotropic hardening parameters derived from machined coupon testing; (c) perform friction coefficient sensitivity study over the range 0.1–0.4 and bound its contribution to yield force uncertainty. No offset rationale is claimed; the shortfalls are substantive and require remediation.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
